720198f.title: Manhattan: Greenwich Street - Dey Street
720198f.text:
Greenwich Street, at Dey Street, showing the ''El'' station
at the S.E. corner under construction. This view shows
the Dey Street side, as the ''El'' tracks are on Greenwich
Street. To the right center are buildings at the S.W.
corner of this intersection.
Kings ''Handbook of New York'' states that the inventor
Charles C. Harvey was permitted to build an experimental
track along Greenwich Street from the Battery to 29th St.
If it succeeded he was to have permission to exxtend the
line to the Harlem River, but if it failed he was to take
it down. The system was commenced in 1867 and the means
of locomotion was a wire rope drawn by a stationary engine.
The method was unsuccessful and the matter lay in sbayence
for several years. The company failed in 1870 and was suc-
ceeded by the New York Elevated Railroad Co. which began
the use of small locomotives on the tracks.

720199f.title: Manhattan: Greenwich Street - Dey Street
720199f.text:
Greenwich Street, south from Dey Street, showing the
first ''El' tracks on the east side, and the Dey Street
station under construction. The latter is at the S.E.
corner. To the right is Cortlandt Street.
For sdditional views of this experimental line see items
on Ninth Avenue at 29th Street, and 13th Street.
1867-8
Gift of Major Quinn

719307f-a.text:
